  "prompt": "Are there legal frameworks in place to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are extensive and well-established legal frameworks in place worldwide to combat money laundering (AML). These frameworks are implemented at both the international and national levels.  Here's a breakdown:\n\n**International Frameworks:**\n\n*   **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** This is the primary international body setting standards and promoting effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. FATF develops \"Recommendations,\" often referred to as the \"FATF 40 Recommendations,\" which are the internationally recognized global standard for AML/CFT (Combating the Financing of Terrorism).  Countries commit to implementing these recommendations. FATF also conducts mutual evaluations of countries to assess their compliance with these standards.\n\n*   **United Nations Conventions:** The UN plays a significant role through various conventions:\n    *   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):**  One of the earliest major international treaties focusing on money laundering related to drug trafficking.\n    *   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC, 2000):**  Addresses money laundering related to all forms of organized crime.\n    *   **International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999):**  Deals with money laundering linked to terrorism financing.\n    *   **United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC, 2003):**  Covers money laundering related to corruption.\n\n*   **Regional Bodies:** Many regional organizations also have AML/CFT initiatives and standards. Examples include:\n    *   The Council of Europe's MONEYVAL\n    *   The Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering (APG)\n    *   The Caribbean Financial Action Task Force (CFATF)\n    *   "